ed consisting of solar photovoltaics, wind turbine, microturbine, battery array, and electric boiler. The microgrid is grid-connected and designed to supply both heat and power. It is constrained to meet 100% of the energy demand. An optimal design is found to minimize the cost of energy supply over a 20 year lifespan. The optimal design is analysed with respect to technology cost and environmental policy in the form of CO<inf>2</inf> taxation. Use of combined heat and power is found to lower cost of energy supply in all cases. CO<inf>2</inf> taxation is found to be ineffective in promoting greener power supply for this system unless coupled with reductions in renewable technology cost. Â© 2014 Elsevier B.V.</ce:para></abstract></dc:description><link href="http://api.elsevier.com/content/abstract/scopus_id/84904349579" rel="self"/><link href="http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?partnerID=HzOxMe3b&amp;scp=84904349579&amp;origin=inward" rel="scopus"/><link href="http://api.elsevier.com/content/search/scopus?query=refeid%282-s2.0-84904349579%29" rel="cited-by"/></coredata><affiliation href="http://api.elsevier.com/content/affiliation/affiliation_id/60029445" id="60029445"><affilname>University of Minnesota Twin Cities</affilname></affiliation><affiliation href="http://api.elsevier.com/content/affiliation/affiliation_id/60002306" id="60002306"><affilname>University of Calgary</affilname></affiliation><authors><author auid="56272754600" seq="1"><ce:initials>M.</ce:initials><ce:indexed-name>Zachar M.</ce:indexed-name><ce:surname>Zachar</ce:surname><ce:given-name>Michael</ce:given-name><preferred-name><ce:initials>M.</ce:initials><ce:indexed-name>Zachar M.</ce:indexed-name><ce:surname>Zachar</ce:surname><ce:given-name>Michael</ce:given-name></preferred-name><author-url>http://api.elsevier.com/content/author/author_id/56272754600</author-url><affiliation href="http://api.elsevier.com/content/affiliation/affiliation_id/60029445" id="60029445"/></author><author auid="2303